RESEARCH PROJECTS
Topology-Embedded Temporal Attention for Fine-Grained Skeleton-Based Action Recognition
In recent years, graph convolutional networks (GCNs) have been extensively applied in numerous fields,
demonstrating strong performances. Although existing GCN-based models have extraordinary feature representation
capabilities in spatial modelling and perform exceptionally well in skeleton-based action recognition, they work
poorly for fine-grained recognition. The key issue involves tiny distinctions between multiple classes. To address this
issue, we propose a novel module named the Topology-Embedded Temporal Attention Module (TE-TAM). Through
embedding the temporal-different topology modelled with local area skeleton points in spatial and temporal
dimensions, The TE-TAM achieves dynamic attention learning for the temporal dimensions of distinct data samples,
capturing minor differences among intra-frames and inter-frames, making the characteristics more discriminating, and
increasing the distances between various classes. To verify the validity of the proposed module, we inserted the
module into the GCN-based models and tested them on FSD-30. Experimental results show that the GCN-based
models with TE-TAMs outperformed the property of previous GCN-based models.
Figure.1 TE-TAM framework
Role and Responsibilities: I proposed the TE-TAM framework, did all the validation experiments and finished
the first draft of paper.
Collaboration: Discussion and revision of algorithm details and revision of our paper.
Final Achievements:
1. Published in Applied Sciences; 2022, 12(16), 8023; https://doi.org/10.3390/app12168023
Authors: Pengyuan Han; Zhongli Ma; Jiajia Liu
Protein Structure Predicts Enzyme Activity
We collated Km and Kcat data from the BRENDA database and the literature to form a preliminary dataset. With the
publicly available dataset, the team collated negative example data of enzymes and substrates, and matched the
enzyme sequences with the structures predicted by AlphaFold to form an enzyme activity dataset containing enzyme
structure data. The enzyme activity values were ranked by the natural breakpoint method, and the enzyme activity
classes were specified for classification and prediction. Based on the transformer model, the enzyme activity was
predicted by considering the enzyme sequence, enzyme structure and compound data, and the results were evaluated.
Role and Responsibilities: Responsible for enzyme activity prediction algorithm framework design and code
writing.
Collaboration: What we faced is not only the challenge itself, but also the way how we from different disciplinary
backgrounds communicate and collaborate effectively. Therefore, in the early stage, we maintained a high frequency
of communication and learning to minimize the communication gap between us. My previous studies and
competitions had nothing to do with proteins, but there were many analogies that could be applied to the
representation of protein structure encoding. Therefore, I am fortunate to be the model architecture designer and do
the code implementation in our team.

RoboMaster2022: Robot Automatic Recognition and Hitting System Based on Computer Vision
Based on computer vision, target pose estimation, filtering algorithms, and projectile motion models, we construct an
algorithmic framework for automatic recognition and targeting. Based on this framework(Shown in Figure.2), we
tested and optimized different target detection, pose estimation and filtering algorithms, which are finally validated on
infantry, sentry and hero robots in the RoboMaster2022 competition.
Role and Responsibilities: I am the leader of the group Robot Vision Perception in RoboMaster Season 22. I lead
the group to complete the robot vision perception tasks in RoboMaster competitions. I designed the framework of the
robot vision perception algorithm for the whole season and planned the development tasks for the whole season.
Collaboration: I was involved in all the development tasks of the group. Robot is a complex system, therefore,
sometimes it is really hard to find the root of one question. Thus, the most challenging but interesting is working with
other groups to get the best performance out of the whole robot. The most impressive in our R&D was the period
where we solved the muzzle shake problem. We started from both the control system and the visual perception
algorithm, combined with the derivation of mathematical models and experimental verification to determine the root
cause of the muzzle jitter.

The 16th National Intelligent Car Competition for College Students: Intelligent perception of
spatial information for Logistics Robots
I divide the system into three components: determination of relative position (computer vision localization),
recognition of traffic light signals (object detection), lane line detection and tracking (object segmentation and
tracking). Firstly, calculating the position through detecting the Aruco code. Secondly, I carried out two solutions for
traffic light detection. The first solution is that combining the machine learning algorithm and traditional computer
vision algorithm. Using the predefined Haar feature, for example, to represent the feature of traffic light image. Then
training a classifier with those features. The second solution is through a light CNN to recognize the traffic light. And
I finally deploy it on the Jetson nano through TensorRT. Thirdly, it is the traffic line tracking part. I firstly trained a
object segment neural network, which is a light network, called U-Net, by pytorch framework. Then, I used a
mathematical method to fit the traffic line, getting a math formula. Finally, combining the Pure-Pursuit algorithm to
control the car. And, the three parts are combined using the framework shown in figure.4.
Final Achievements:
1. The Second Prize in The Southern Division Contest and the Third Prize in The National Final Contest of the 16th
National Intelligent Car Competition for College Students in August 2021
2. The Third Prize in the National Final Contest of the 2nd Aerospace Cup Mobile Robot AI Innovation Technology
Challenge in August 2021

Pedestrian Tracking System
This system, shown in figure.7, consists of three main parts: detector, ReID feature extractor and a tracking module,
named DeepSort. I did not choose a one-shot algorithm, like fairmot or so on, because I think the two-stages
algorithm is much more flexible, no matter in improving the tracking accuracy or in promoting the infer speed. There
are several choice in each stage. I firstly conducted various experiments on the detector. I chose different detectors,
such as one-stage detector like PP-YOLO, two-stages detector like Fast-RCNN or even some modified version by
myself. Then, I test them on different datasets, like ‘CrowdHuman’ and ‘MOT’ series, even with a dataset which
merging them all together. I also carried out various experiments on ReID module to choose a suitable feature
extractor for DeepSort module among ShuffleNe, GhostNet and ResNet with Market-1501 dataset. Finally, they were
combined together with the framework shown in figure.7.
Figure.8 The algorithm framework of the Pedestrian Tracking System.
Figure.9 The tracking performance of the system.

ENTREPRENEURSHIP EXPERIENCE
WeChat Answering Robot
In March 2022, I joined an AI anti-epidemic WeChat robot public welfare project initiated by developers in
Shanghai, which integrates policy Q&A and antigen kit result detection, aiming to improve the work efficiency of
grassroots government workers under the epidemic lockdown. I led the development of antigen kit result detection
capabilities. Since then, the WeChat robot has continued to serve grassroots workers until September 2022, when we
decided to take it to a major upgrade to better meet the needs of grassroots government workers, reduce their working
pressure and improve their working efficiency. It was also with this opportunity that we turned the newly upgraded
version into a commercial project. And signed a one-year service contract with Shanghai Linfen Street Office, with a
service fee of 100,000 yuan.
Figure 4 shows a schematic diagram of one part of our business algorithm frameworks. I am responsible for the
algorithm development of ‘Document Process’ and ‘Answer’ capabilities. And, the ‘Answer’ part algorithm was
developed based on RocketQA(as shown in figure 5) framework.
Role and Responsibilities: In this project, I am responsible for the WeChat robot algorithm development of
‘Document Process’ and ‘Answer’ capabilities. And, as shown in figure 5, my equity in our team is 9%.
Collaboration: In fact, this is a very complex engineering task. We need to consider many things beyond
technology, such as user experience, user Q&A habits, and so on. These factors will affect our specific algorithm
design to some extent. Therefore, in this project, my main partnerships, apart from collaboration with algorithm
colleagues, are more focused on exchanging and collaborating with product manager.
Final Achievements: We finally signed a one-year service contact with Shanghai Linfen Street Officer, with a
service fee of 100,000 yuan.
